    Overview

    This guide exists to help CPE teams codify & re-create their existing infrastructure under the CPE Development (awdevelopment). The reasoning for this is twofold

    1. To support a launch into Canada

    2. To support a future migration from USDFS

    This documentation has written by the UPS team, our remit is

    • Collaborating with CPE-Devops to setup the new CPE accounts/environments in order to support V1 services

    • Creating infrastructure under CPE Development (awdevelopment) using Terraform

    • Codifying infrastructure under under CPE Development (awdevelopment) that exists in USDFS but is not managed by Terraform

    How can I contact UPS?

    If you have any questions please reach out on #cpe-infra-migration-team

    What will awdevelopment be used for?

    At this time you can think of CPE Development (awdevelopment) as a proof-of-concept that we can spin up Canada correctly (this applies to V1 & PDM services).

    • V1 Devstacks (AFAIK) will still work as they currently do i.e. cloudformation under the Legacy Development account.

    • AFAIK there is no plans to start setting up V1 devstacks in awdevelopment yet.

    JIRA admin

    If you’re a team being asked to Terraform your services you should already have an INIT under PROG-401.

    Our recommended Jira process is:

    • create an Epic per service in your team’s Jira project

    • create a task to assess the service’s current infrasturcture and level of IaC

    • using the output of that, create tasks for the remaining work.

    Team’s use Jira differently and this isn’t prescriptive. But please make sure work is linked to your INIT and the normal status and date fields on the init are kept up to date to help with programme tracking.

    Has work been done on my service already?

    Please see UPS CPE Service List

     

    V3/Podium Services

    Please reach out to CPE Devops for support on migration V3/Podium services to Podium CPE clusters.

    Migration Steps

    Assess the service’s infrastructure

    If this work is being complete by a service team and not UPS then this section is optional. However it may be beneficial to complete this for posterity.

    Before creating infrastructure we should perform an audit on the service to establish

    • What infrastructure is owned by a service?

    • What is managed by Terraform?

    • What is not managed by Terraform?

    • What infrastructure dependencies between services?

    e.g. Prohibited Participants

    Please

    1. Create an audit using the Service Template , all audit live under the UPS CPE Service List page.

    2. Meet with the team to discuss the findings (OPTIONAL : Some services may be simplistic and are not modified very often)

      1. Teams should be aware of what infrastructure their own

      2. Teams may give insight as to what infrastructure is still required or ongoing Terraform work that may conflict with UPS work e.g. DB upgrades/migrations.

      3. Teams may own infra that is not directly used by the service

    How do I identify what infrastructure a service uses?

    Search for resources on Puppet configuration files

    V1 service configuration is found in the Puppet repository, we can look here to discover what infrastructure the service is configured to talk to.

    A a lot of Java V1 services utilise the JCM framework,

    • this has support for managing queues & topics based on puppet configuration. For the vast majority of V1 services these resources will not be managed by Terraform. The puppet configuration typically looks something like…

      • Events.Transaction.Publisher.Connection.Type=SNS Events.Transaction.Publisher.Topic.Arn=arn:aws:sns:us-east-1:990163193419:production-financeledger-transaction-events-topic Events.Transaction.EnablePublishing=true Events.Transaction.Publisher.Service.Endpoint=sns.us-east-1.amazonaws.com Events.Transaction.Publisher.Signing.Region=us-east-1 ... Events.FixupDelay.Connection.Type=SQS Events.FixupDelay.Queue.Name=production-financeledger-fixup-delay-events-queue Events.FixupDelay.Queue.MessageReceiverCount=2 Events.FixupDelay.EnableSubscribing=true

    • this framework also has support for connecting to databases, it typically looks something like…

      • WalletBrokerRO.Host=ro.walletbroker.db.use1.prod.us.fdbox.net WalletBrokerRO.Name=walletbroker WalletBrokerRO.User=walletbrokerro ...

    Please note this method is not recommended as

    1. These hosts serve production traffic & commands ran there should be treated with caution

    2. Some hosts do not permit root permissions

      1. Access may be limited to certain specific FanDuel employees

      2. By default access is not given to non FanDuel employees

    3. Configuration may contain sensitive information that should not be posted onto confluence (passwords, keys etc).

    Another method is to ssh onto one of the service hosts

    1. Look up the service host via https://cpanel.east.fdbox.net/

    2. Open a secure shell

      1. e.g. ssh root@<service>-prod-bionic-<instance-id>.east.fdbox.net

    3. Print the output of the service’s configuration file

      1. For Java services this can found at

        1. cat /opt/<service>/config/production-puppet.properties

      2. For python services this can be found at

        1. cat /opt/<service>/settings/production.settings

    Search for resources on AWS Console

    Not everything will be present on a configuration file and even some resources won’t be part of what teams know about their services. One example is Route53 and the records and template instances used by Jenkins jobs to generate the launch template for the service’s ASG.

    Places (AWS Services) worth checking to reveal the presence of resources related to the service are:

    • Route53

    • EC2

    • KMS

    Generally using the service name would suffice to find the resources. In some cases, the search tool does not implement the contains’s search which may hide results.

    Search for resources on previously identified resources

    Inspecting all resources that were already identified is a good source to find new ones that are linked to them. For example, there are some IAM policies and roles used by services through its EC2 instances. KMS policies might attached to queues. S3 buckets might contain event subscription. SNS topics can show queues that subscribe to it and so on.

    Ensure service’s Terraform is in sync with AWS

    Infrastructure pipelines for V1 services are separate from deploys (e.g. Ledger's infra pipeline is not triggered by its Cpanel deploy mechanism), as a result teams don’t often run their infra pipeline.

    This means there can be drift between Terraform and AWS, for example this can happen because…

    • There have been changes via the console .e.g. to upgrade DB/EC2 instance sizes or to add additional database replicas. These can be made by Devops as a result of a support incident for example.

    • The service may be scaled out with Terraform via the GameDay/Superbowl prescale mechanism

      • https://jenkins.fdbox.net/operations/job/ASG_Pre-game_Scaling

      • https://github.com/fanduel/aws-helpers/tree/masterConnect your Github account

    • Develops may have made changes to infra in the Perftest AWS account

    Before we attempt to modularise any Legacy terraform we should try ensure that Terraform is in sync AWS, i.e. the plan reports zero changes.

    If necessary we should

    • Reach out to the team that own the service & understand why Terraform is out of sync

      • e.g. are they mid database migration?

    • Raise a PR to update Terraform so it reports no changes to the plan

    Why is this important?

    • We don’t want to accidentally apply changes that negatively impact production

    • Terraform should be kept up to date incase those on support are required to make Terraform changes

    Upgrade Terraform

    As of 12 Oct 2023 the latest recommend Terraform version that works with InfraDeploy is 1.5 - see https://fanduel.slack.com/archives/CHJR8RCMQ/p1697103081216229Connect your Slack account

    We should also upgrade the teams terraform version (infrastructure/deploy-service.yaml) to match 1.5. At a minimum UPS require Terraform to be at version 1.1 for us to utilise the moved command as part of the Legacy Terraform modularisation.

    Ensure asset-tagging is in place

    We should make sure that the asset-tagging strategy is in place for the service. Please see Migration: Get Cataloged but as a TL;DR:

    • Ensure a service.datadog.yaml file is in place in the root of the repo

      • The DataDog Service Catalog Metadata Template (v2.1) page covers the format required of this.

    • Add aws: tagging-mode: "implicit" to deploy-service.yaml under the terraform: block

      • There is also an explicit mode for those who wish to specify variables themselves.

    • Remove any module "aws_tags" blocks and any tags = ... lines from resources

    N.b. Teams should already have an open PR on their service that adds the service catalogue (CAKE). This can be extended to support asset tagging e.g. https://github.com/fanduel/transaction-notification/pull/122Connect your Github account

    Modularising Terraform Code

    A lot of V1 services have infrastructure partly managed by Terraform that target the Legacy accounts (see UPS CPE Infrastructure Guide | What do you mean by Legacy accounts? ).

    To avoid potentially impacting existing infrastructure teams need a way of managing new infastructure in the CPE accounts in isolation from Legacy.

    The solution UPS has came up with is to refactor Terraform code to have two modules

    1. Legacy: Contains Terraform code targeting Legacy accounts e.g. USDFS

    2. CPE: Contains Terraform code targeting the new CPE accounts - this is code is completely separate and should in no way effect Legacy.

    Tip! Favor creating a branch for starting modularizing the terraform code into the legacy module. See this Pull Request for reference of the changes that might be necessary.

    How do we want teams structure their legacy code?

    Tip! This approach is recommended if…

    1. You don’t have all of your infrastructure under the Legacy accounts managed by Terraform. This is because this approach avoids you having to import existing Legacy infra

    2. You want the ability to write new Terraform code in isolation from how your Legacy code is written.

    Infra Deploy is the tool that runs on the pipelines and performs terraform actions. This tool allows teams to organise their Terraform code in different ways. In order to support the Legacy/CPE modularisation we want to refactor code to use the “environment” based approach (shown below in green).

    infrastructure/

    terraform/

    aws/

    environments/

    infrastructure ├── main.tf ├── outputs.tf └── variables.tf
    infrastructure └── terraform ├── main.tf ├── outputs.tf └── variables.tf
    infrastructure └── aws ├── main.tf ├── outputs.tf └── variables.tf
    infrastructure ├── deploy-service.yaml ├── environments │   ├── awdevelopment │   │   ├── main.tf │   │   └── etc.... │   └── usdfs │   ├── main.tf │   ├── etc..... └── modules ├── cpe │   ├── iam.tf │   ├── main.tf │   ├── service.tf │   ├── sqs.tf │   └── variables.tf │   └── etc.... └── legacy ├── main.tf └── variables.tf └── etc...

    My service already has all of it’s infrastructure codified, do I need to follow this “environments” approach?

    The idea behind the environments approach is that it allows teams to create new infra targeting the CPE accounts in relative isolation from whats in “Legacy”.  It was written with V1 services in mind, so these typically have some of their “Legacy” infra managed by Terraform and the rest by something else e.g. JCM.  This allows them to not have to deal with importing existing resources in order to add a new variables file for a new environment.

    If you…

    • You have all of your infrastructure under the Legacy accounts managed by Terraform.

    • And you are satisfied with your current Terraform code and simply wish to apply it to a new environment

    … then you don’t need to use the “environments” approach.

    Some examples of this…

    • https://github.com/fanduel/reality-check/tree/master/infrastructure/awsConnect your Github account

    • https://github.com/fanduel/user-risk-scores/tree/master/infrastructure/awsConnect your Github account

    Creating the Legacy Module

    First up we need to encapsulate all existing TF logic within a new module.

    1. Under the infrastructure folder create the folders modules/legacy

    2. Moving all existing terraform code into modules/legacy

    3. Under the infrastructure folder create the folder environments

    Creating Environment files

    Now that we’ve bundled existing TF code into a legacy module we need a way to “run” this module for a given legacy environment (.e.g. perftest or usdfs etc).

    1. Create a folder for each environment that this service supports e.g.

      1. environments/perftest

      2. environments/usdfs

    2. Copy modules/legacy/variables.tf to environments/<env>/variables.tf

    3. Create the folder environments/<env>/variables/

    4. Copy the variable files at modules/legacy/variables/<env>.tfvars (& modules/legacy/variables/<env>.enc.tfvars) to environments/<env>/variables/

    5. Copy any contexts at modules/legacy/variables/contexts to environments/<env>/variables/contexts

      1. E.g. we would copy something like modules/legacy/variables/contexts/defaults.tfvars to all envs e.g. environments/perftest/variables/contexts/defaults.tfvars, environments/usdfs/variables/contexts/defaults.tfvars. However if the context was something like modules/legacy/variables/contexts/perftest.tfvars then it should only be copied to the appropriate location e.g. environments/perftest/variables/contexts/perftest.tfvars

    6. Create a environments/<env>/main.tf file, it should outline the required providers and reference the legacy module… (Note: v4.67.0 of the AWS provider is just an example. You can update this to a later version if you choose, Versions are documented on the official provider page)

      1. terraform { required_providers { aws = { source = "hashicorp/aws" version = "4.67.0" # Please update this version when working on this module } } } module "legacy" { source = "../../modules/legacy" # Here we want to reference any variables that this module requires. # A tip - you can use your IDE to autogenerated the list from modules/legacy/variables.tf foo = var.foo bar = var.bar etc... }

    7. Create a environments/<env>/moved.tf file, this will allow us to tell Terraform that we’ve moved the resources and they should not be counted as a “change”. It’s this step that will provide us with an identical plan output to main/master - see TF docs on “moved”.

      1. To create this file we have to go through every defined resource or module and tell Terraform where it came from and where it has now moved to.

      2. moved { from = data.aws_ami.silver to = module.legacy.data.aws_ami.silver } moved { from = module.prohibitedparticipants_aurora to = module.legacy.module.prohibitedparticipants_aurora } moved { from = aws_db_parameter_group.prohibitedparticipantsdb_parameter_group to = module.legacy.aws_db_parameter_group.prohibitedparticipantsdb_parameter_group } etc...

    8. Lastly now that we have extracted our variables we can delete modules/legacy/variables as it is no longer necessary.

    Running the Terraform Plan and confirming equivalency

    Now that we’ve refactored the existing Terraform code we need to confirm that we haven’t broke anything…

    1. Locate the services infrastructure pipeline e.g. https://buildkite.com/fanduel/prohibited-participants-infrastructure

    2. Run the Terraform plan steps for the existing environments (branch = origin/main or origin/master)

      1. Please be careful that the team’s pipeline won’t auto apply, we do not want to adversely impact legacy infrastructure in production. We can confirm this by…

        1. Looking at existing Terraform builds

        2. Double checking the buildkite logic e.g. buildkite/infra.yml (or however its named).

    3. Commit and push our changes

    4. Compare the outputted plans between your branch and origin/main , they should be identical & the pipeline should pass e.g.

      1. e.g. TODO - Get a screenshot with the pipeline passing, this was failing due to an unrelated issue.

      2. If they are not then

        1. We’ve missed something, or made a mistake

        2. The INFRA has changed whilst we’ve been making changes

        3. Reach out to the UPS team for support

    Apply Legacy Module changes

    Once we have modularised the existing Legacy terraform code our next steps should be

    1. A UPS/Devops review (optional)

      1. see UPS CPE Infrastructure Guide | How can I contact UPS?

    2. A review from the codeowners

    3. Apply the changes in whatever environments their pipeline supports e.g. perftest, usdfs

    4. Remove the environments/<env>/moved.tf files e.g. https://github.com/fanduel/transaction-notification/pull/118Connect your Github account

    Creating the CPE Module

    Before starting with the CPE module, it’s best to review the existing core infrastructure (IAM policies, IAM roles, Security Groups, etc…) that has been provisioned to support your services. This can be found here: Core Infrastructure

    If you feel that there is some infrastructure that is missing, please do reach out to us in the #cpe-infra-migration-team channel and we’d be happy to help.

    We now have puppet infrastructure provisioned in the CPE Development account. Previously, it was required to provide the templating_silver_image_owner_id variable, as this was used to determine the silver image AMI to use for your template an asg instances. As we now have specific silver image AMI’s to support the CPE Development account, this value is not required anymore.

    More information on this can be found here: UPS Using Puppet in the CPE Development account

    Next we need a place to put our new infrastructure that we will be creating under the CPE accounts.

    Infrastructure within this module…

    • may be a near identical copy and paste of what is in the legacy module if it already matches UPS’s best practices.

    • may include infra that is not managed by Terraform (e.g. SQS’s managed by JCM)

    • may be refactored slightly to incorporate best practices UPS identifies (e.g. the use of Fanduel internal modules).

    1. Under the infrastructure folder create the folders modules/cpe, this will contains scripts for all of your new infra.

    2. Add a main.tf file to the modules/cpe folder, at a minimum we’ll need access to FanDuels resource catalogue.

      1. module "fd_resource_registry" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-fd-resource-registry.git?ref=v<LATEST-VERSION>" }

    3. Under the environments folder create the folder for the CPE environments you wish to target e.g. awdevelopment

      1. TODO Link the environment state

    Updating the Infra Pipeline

    We should extend a team’s existing infra pipeline to support the CPE awdevelopment account. Until we get things "working" there should also be a blocked destroy step for awdevelopment env only.

    The context for CENTRAL services should be uscentral1.

    steps: ############################################ # LEGACY ACCOUNTS ############################################ - pipe-gen: type: group/infra-deploy args: account_name: perftest context_name: perftest plan_if: "build.branch != pipeline.default_branch" apply_if: "build.branch == pipeline.default_branch" block_before_apply: true - pipe-gen: type: group/infra-deploy args: account_name: usdfs context_name: prod apply_if: "build.branch == pipeline.default_branch" block_before_apply: true ############################################ # CPE ACCOUNTS ############################################ - pipe-gen: type: group/infra-deploy args: account_name: awdevelopment context_name: uscentral1 block_before_apply: true # Block for input - input: ":thinking_face: Destroy in awdevelopment" key: infra-deploy:awdevelopment:destroy:block # Destroy - depends_on: - infra-deploy:awdevelopment:destroy:block pipe-gen: type: step/infra-deploy args: action: destroy account_name: awdevelopment context_name: uscentral1

    Creating new CPE infrastructure

    • Please see the following page for a list of UPS recommended Terraform modules: UPS Terraform Modules

    • Please try and contribute missing functionality to these modules before opting not to use them

    Now we have a new “CPE” module what do we actually put in it? The desire is to recreate existing infra and manage anything that isn’t already managed Terraform e.g. queues, topics etc. In addition to this we wish to apply best practices where feasible.

    We should be creating a like for like comparison with infrastructure in USDFS where it makes sense to do so (obviously in awdevelopment we don't need resources scaled to production equivalents).

    Variables and Inputs

    Where possible, we should aim to reduce the number of inputs/variables required for a service. Ideally only things that can change between environments should be defined as variables. Anything else should be defined at the resource level. This helps to reduce the complexity of the inputs for each service.

    Where possible, where inputs are consistent across environments (eg. security groups, IAM policies, etc…), we should aim to use data resources, rather than rely on variable inputs. This helps to reduce complexity of terraform by reducing the number of variables/inputs required for each service.

    Tags

    We should avoid using the tf-module-aws-tags & instead rely on asset tagging via Infra Deploy and the Datadog catalog files.

    SQS

    • Should be placed in an infrastructure/modules/cpe/sqs.tf

    • Should match their production equivalents for parity between environments

      • e.g. in terms of encryption, Message Retention Period, Delivery Delay etc etc.

    • Should be named in line with UPS naming conventions

    • Should consider avoiding the use of customer managed keys if Terraform is being used to support devstacks

      • This is because prefixing the deploy context can lead to a KMS key being created per devstacks. The Ledger services discovered this was the case for their WTSS service leading to a cost of $500 per week vs mere dollars in production.

    • We should look to adopt the following module at the latest stable version: tf-module-sqs-queue e.g.

      • SQS With Dead Letter Queue Example

        • module "service_description_dlq" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-sqs-queue.git?ref=v0.6.1" name = "${var.deploy_context}-service-description-dlq" random_policy_sid = true encryption_enabled = false } module "service_description_sqs" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-sqs-queue.git?ref=v0.6.1" name = "${var.deploy_context}-service-description-queue" dead_letter_queue = module.service_description_dlq.queue_arn random_policy_sid = true encryption_enabled = false }
    My SQS subscribes to an SNS that does not yet exist?

    We can use a conditional to manage the subscription subscribe_to_sns_arns = var.connect_to_sns ? [var.sns_arn] : [] until such a time that the SNS does exist.

    How do I use the SQS policy document output?
    myvar = module.my_queue.policy

    We can also combine the policies of multiples queues but be aware with this approach may breach the policy document length limit.

    data "aws_iam_policy_document" "combined" { source_policy_documents = [ module.sqs_finance_ledger_transaction_events.policy, module.sqs_transaction_event_cache_updated_events.policy, module.sqs_transaction_event_cache_updated_retry_events.policy ] } resource "aws_iam_policy" "wallet-transaction-summary" { name = "wallet-transaction-summary-${terraform.workspace}" description = "Wallet transaction summary service AWS IAM Policy" policy = data.aws_iam_policy_document.combined.json }
    How can I look up another service’s topic to subscribe to?

    We can utilise Terraform's data block to look up existing infra e.g.

    data "aws_sns_topic" "financepayments_deposit_completed_events_topic" { name = "${var.deploy_context}-financepayments-deposit-completed-events-topic" } # Reference it's outputs # data.aws_sns_topic.financepayments_deposit_completed_events_topic.<output> # e.g. data.aws_sns_topic.financepayments_deposit_completed_events_topic.arn
    Our queue is currently managed by JCM, how do we stop it trying to create the queue?

    In your puppet properties utilise URL instead of NAME e.g. the following assumes the SQS exists and will not attempt to create it.

    Listener.Queue.Notifications.Connection.Type=SQS Listener.Queue.Notifications.Queue.URL=https://sqs.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/952224021780/uscentral1-notification-request-queue Listener.Queue.Notifications.Queue.MessageReceiverCount=5000 Listener.Queue.Notifications.Queue.RetryMessageDelay=30

    Our topic is currently managed by JCM, how do we stop it trying to create the queue?

    In your puppet properties utilise ARN instead of NAME e.g. the following assumes the SNS exists and will not attempt to create it.

    ExclusionChanges.Publisher.Connection.Type=SNS ExclusionChanges.Publisher.Topic.Arn=arn:aws:sns:us-east-1:564588860590:us_perftest-userinfo-exclusion-changes-topic

    How do I store/encrypt the master password?

    You’ll notice in these examples (UPS CPE Infrastructure Guide | Do you have any recent examples of RDS in awdevelopment? ) that we store the master password in an encrypted file (e.g here).

    To do the same

    1. create the file with the intended password e.g.

      1. infrastructure/environments/awdevelopment/variables/awdevelopment.enc.tfvars.json

      2. { "db_master_password": "Pod1um#DB" }

    2. assume the AWS role on the command line: arn:aws:iam::580803390928:role/DeveloperFullAdmin

    3. Run: fd-encryption-cli -k arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:446345481538:alias/infrastructure-deploy-service-awdevelopment -f awdevelopment.enc.tfvars.json

    4. This should result in the file looking something like….

      1. { "db_master_password": "ENC[type:str,data:AQICAHhVqt9Z4DnY42rVpSclUVvd5qFPaUfakF/eomV+na3h1QF7EYC2xJq6SgSmuzr98hVIAAAAZzBlBgkqhkiG9w0BBwagWDBWAgEAMFEGCSqGSIb3DQEHATAeBglghkgBZQMEAS4wEQQMHOkR4KowVUDcG3R8AgEQgCTXxqY1XqVGre1Yi94nzWkcmObW8NkxbwSpN3zmtboueJWkb7s=]" }

    For more info please see: fd-encryption-cli

    Required security groups were not added by terraform?

    1. Check you are using the correct variable vpc_security_group_ids for passing security groups to the cluster module.

    How can I give my EC2 instances permission to interact with my queues & topics?

    The tf-module-sqs-queue & tf-module-sns-topic outputs json policy documents that you can choose to use. These should already contain all the permissions you require.

    For a single SQS you can do the following…

    infrastructure/modules/cpe/sns.tf

    module "my_sqs" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-sqs-queue.git?ref=vXXX" name = "${var.deploy_context}-service-description-queue" }

    infrastructure/modules/cpe/service.tf

    module "service" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-fd-cpe-service.git?ref=v2.0.3" ...etc... service_additional_managed_policies = [ module.my_sqs.policy ]

    If you have a small number of queues & topics you can combine the policies. It is important to enable random_policy_sid to prevent statement ids from clashing.

    infrastructure/modules/cpe/sns.tf

    module "my_sqs" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-sqs-queue.git?ref=vXXX" name = "${var.deploy_context}-service-description-queue" random_policy_sid = true } module "my_topic" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-sns-topic.git?ref=vXXX" name = "${var.deploy_context}-service-description-topic" random_policy_sid = true } etc....

    infrastructure/modules/cpe/iam.tf

    data "aws_iam_policy_document" "combined" { source_policy_documents = [ module.my_sqs_1.policy, module.my_topic.policy ] } resource "aws_iam_policy" "sns_sqs_policy" { name = "${var.deploy_context}-service-policy" description = "Service SNS/SQS Policy" policy = data.aws_iam_policy_document.combined.json }

    infrastructure/modules/cpe/service.tf

    module "service" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-fd-cpe-service.git?ref=v2.0.3" ...etc... service_additional_managed_policies = [ aws_iam_policy.sns_sqs_policy.arn, ]

    If you have many queues/topics then combining the polices can lead you to you breaching the AWS policy document size, in this case its best to either

    • Use for loop to create topics & queues (that have the same configuration) and modify the policy to include all of the resources you wish…

      • TODO EXample

    • Or simply define your own policy…

    data "aws_iam_policy_document" "userinfo_sns_sqs" { statement { sid = "AllowSNSProvision" effect = "Allow" actions = [ "SNS:Subscribe", "SNS:Publish", "SNS:Receive", "SNS:ListTopics", "SNS:AddPermission", "SNS:ListSubscriptionsByTopic", "SNS:SetTopicAttributes", "SNS:GetTopicAttributes" # You may require KMS permissions if your SNS is encrypted ] resources = [ module.rg_timeout_expiry_notification_topic.topic_arn, module.rg_exclusion_changes_topic.topic_arn, module.userinfo_user_topic.topic_arn, module.userinfo_user_attributes_topic.topic_arn, module.userinfo_user_status_changed_topic.topic_arn, module.userinfo_user_created_events_topic.topic_arn, data.aws_sns_topic.financepayments_deposit_completed_events_topic.arn, data.aws_sns_topic.authgateway_user_created_events_topic.arn ] } statement { sid = "AllowSQSProvision" effect = "Allow" actions = [ "SQS:DeleteQueue", "SQS:GetQueueUrl", "SQS:ListQueues", "SQS:SetQueueAttributes", "SQS:GetQueueAttributes", "SQS:SendMessage", "SQS:SendMessageBatch", "SQS:ReceiveMessage", "SQS:DeleteMessage", "SQS:DeleteMessageBatch", "SQS:AddPermission", "SQS:ChangeMessageVisibility", "SQS:ChangeMessageVisibilityBatch" # You may require KMS permissions if your SQS is encrypted # You may require KMS permissions if your SNS is encrypted ] resources = [ module.rg_timeout_expiry_notification_dead_letter_queue.queue_arn, module.rg_timeout_expiry_notification_queue.queue_arn, module.rg_user_status_changed_queue.queue_arn, module.userinfo_deposit_completed_events_dead_letter_queue.queue_arn, module.userinfo_deposit_completed_events_queue.queue_arn, module.userinfo_s3notifications_queue.queue_arn, module.userinfo_user_created_events_dead_letter_queue.queue_arn, module.userinfo_user_created_events_queue.queue_arn, module.userinfo_user_segment_updates_queue.queue_arn ] } } resource "aws_iam_policy" "sns_sqs_managed_policy" { name = local.managed_policy_name path = "/" description = "Managed policy for userinfo SNS/SQS" policy = data.aws_iam_policy_document.userinfo_sns_sqs.json }

    Testing CPE infrastructure

    Puppet infrastructure now exists for the CPE Development account. More information on ensuring that you’re using this new infrastrcuture, and making puppet changes in CPE Development can be found here: UPS Using Puppet in the CPE Development account

    23 Nov 2023Access to the ASG Templating process has been restricted to admins, devops & UPS, please reach out if you need this

    Until the environment is ready we can get creative in order to test infra…

    1. We can run the ASGTemplating process manually, typically this is not run by developers but via puppet/cpanel.

      1. See UPS How do I run ASGTemplating and connect to instances? for more detail.

    2. We can manually deploy the JAR onto the host…

      1. Ssh into the host/hosts

      2. run deployagent -v <version> deploy <service_name>

    3. * We can manually tweak puppet properties…

      1. Ssh into the host/hosts as root

      2. Run vi opt/<service>/config/production-puppet.properties

      3. Edit the properties to connect to your new infra

    4. Restart the service

    5. * Tail the logs

      1. Run: tail -f /var/log/<service>info.log

      2. N.b. you may be able to view Datadog logs & metrics but

    6. Smoke test the service

      1. Although please keep in mind other services and dependent infra may not yet exist

      2. Smoke testing is the reponsibility of teams as they know how to best determine if their service is “working”

    *Puppet runs across hosts every ~30 mins so you may find that properties are reverted back periodically.

    *Its likely that you won’t be able to view Datalog logs or metrics.

    What IAM Roles, IAM Policies, Security Groups, etc… exist to support my service?

    As you’re working through terraforming your service, you’ll likely have questions about Security Groups, IAM policies and a range of other core infrastructure. This infrastructure is documented here: Core Infrastructure

    While working on your services, if you come across any core infrastructure that you feel has been missed, please reach out to us in the #cpe-infra-migration-team channel, and we will be happy to help.

    How do we manage bi-directional infrastructure dependencies?

    UPS have seen instances where two services rely on each others infrastructure in order for the Terraform Plan/Apply to be successful e.g.

    UserInfo & Authgateway dependent infra

     

    Until a solution for this can be created we advise building the Terraform code up across multiple applies until dependent infra is in place - this is what FanDuel currently has in place.

    My service utilises RabbitMQ do I need to create this in the CPE accounts?

    There should be ongoing work to move teams off RabbitMQ for notification - this is the recommended action, please see Routing all Transactional Emails through Transaction Notification. There is as yet no RabbitMQ infrastructure within the CPE accounts.

    My service requires a certificate in awdevelopment

    API and Sportsbook adapter both required certificates attached to a public load balancer. In their cases, this is a wildcard fanduel.com certificate. We don’t have a shared certificate in awdevelopment, so a workaround was to create their won certificates for use in a lower environment, and still be able to easily use an existing one in production when we get to deploying that account without the need for any code changes or hacky conditionals per environment.

    We should use the cpe.use1.fndldev.net hosted zone to support public route53 records, and certificates as well.

    Create a new file called environments/awdevelopment/certificate.tf with the following (note this will need to be updated to reflect your requirement):

    ## Data Resource for the public DNS zone ## More Info: https://registry.terraform.io/providers/hashicorp/aws/latest/docs/data-sources/route53_zone data "aws_route53_zone" "public" { name = "cpe.use1.fndldev.net" } ## Create a Certificate ## More info: https://registry.terraform.io/providers/hashicorp/aws/latest/docs/resources/acm_certificate resource "aws_acm_certificate" "example" { domain_name = "exampledata.aws_route53_zone.public.name}" validation_method = "DNS" } ## DNS validation ## More info: https://registry.terraform.io/providers/hashicorp/aws/latest/docs/resources/acm_certificate_validation resource "aws_route53_record" "example" { for_each = { for dvo in aws_acm_certificate.example.domain_validation_options : dvo.domain_name => { name = dvo.resource_record_name record = dvo.resource_record_value type = dvo.resource_record_type } } allow_overwrite = true name = each.value.name records = [each.value.record] ttl = 60 type = each.value.type zone_id = data.aws_route53_zone.public.zone_id } resource "aws_acm_certificate_validation" "example" { certificate_arn = aws_acm_certificate.example.arn validation_record_fqdns = [for record in aws_route53_record.example : record.fqdn] }

    Add the relevant variables to your cpe module in modules/cpe/variables.tf:

    variable "public_zone_id" { type = string description = "Public Zone ID" } variable "public_zone_name" { type = string description = "Public Zone Name" } variable "public_cert_arn" { type = string description = "ACM Cert to attach to load balancer" }

    Once these variables exist, you can pass in the relevant variables when declaring your CPE module in environments/awdeveopment/service.tf:

    module "cpe" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-fd-cpe-service.git?ref=vX.X.X" ... public_zone_id = data.aws_route53_zone.public.zone_id public_zone_name = data.aws_route53_zone.public.name public_cert_arn = aws_acm_certificate.api.arn }

    You can then use these variables within your terraform for things like route53 records:

    resource "aws_route53_record" "example" { zone_id = var.public_zone_id name = "www.${var.public_zone_name}" type = "A" ttl = "300" records = ["10.0.0.1"] }

    When it comes to deploying to Canada production with an existing certificate, you don’t have to create a environments/<environment-name>/certificates.tf file, and you only need to pass in the relevant values for that environment, as this cert will likely be owned by someone else in the business, and example of this below:

    module "cpe" { source = "git@github.com:fanduel/tf-module-fd-cpe-service.git?ref=vX.X.X" ... public_zone_id = <production-canada-public-zone-id> public_zone_name = <production-canada-public-zone-name> public_cert_arn = <production-canada-public-cert-arn> }
